    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix potential crash in SSS detection due to invalid NID2 values\n\n### Summary\nThe `pss_ch_est_nr` function in the SSS detection chain was vulnerable to out-of-bounds array access when provided with invalid NID2 values. This could occur during cell search when the PSS detection algorithm returned erroneous NID2 values outside the valid range [0,2] for normal mode or [0,1] for SL mode.\n\nThe issue manifests as a segmentation fault during initial cell search, particularly in poor RF conditions where PSS detection may produce false positives with invalid NID2 values.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Configure UE for initial cell search\n2. Place UE in environment with poor signal conditions or interference\n3. Start cell search procedure\n4. When PSS detection returns an invalid NID2 (e.g., -1 or 3+), the SSS detection will attempt to access `primary_synchro_nr2[nid2]` with out-of-bounds index\n5. Segmentation fault occurs due to invalid memory access\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_UE_TRANSPORT/sss_nr.c`: Added bounds checking in `pss_ch_est_nr` function to validate NID2 values before array access\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_UE_TRANSPORT/sss_nr.c`: Modified `rx_sss_nr` to properly handle error returns from `pss_ch_est_nr`\n"
}